==Current series (polymer)== In 1988, the Reserve Bank of Australia issued [[plastic]], specifically [[polypropylene]] [[polymer banknotes]] (which were produced by [[Note Printing Australia]]), to commemorate the bicentenary of European settlement in Australia. These notes contained a transparent "window" with an optically variable image of [[Captain James Cook]] as a security feature. Australian banknotes were the first in the world to use such features. All current Australian banknotes also contain [[Microprinting]] for further security.
{|class="wikitable" !colspan="2"|First series (1988) [http://www.rba.gov.au/banknotes/types/index.html] |- |[[File:Australian $10 note commemorative front.jpg|101px|1988 commemorative polymer note - obverse]] |[[File:Australian $10 note commemorative back.jpg|101px|1988 commemorative polymer note - reverse]] |}
There were initial difficulties with the first banknote issued; the $10 note (pictured above) was recalled because of problems with the holographic security feature detaching from the note. However, the Reserve Bank saw potential in the issue of plastic banknotes and commenced preparations for an entirely new series made from [[polymer]], commencing with the $5 note in 1992. In 1995, the design of the $5 note was updated to match the rest of the New Note Series, with additional slight changes in 1996. In 2001, a special commemorative $5 note was produced, but in 2002, the previous version's production commenced again.
In 2002, the design of all notes (except for the $5 note picturing the Queen) was slightly changed to include the names of the people pictured on them under the portraits, and swapping the order of the signatures of officials on the notes.
Today all Australian notes are made of polymer.
